<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759"><gtr:id>AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Hills Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Cambridge</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>CB2 2QH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759"><gtr:id>AB7C0822-BBCB-4C61-85EC-5D13C7A31759</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Hills Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Cambridge</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>CB2 2QH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/C984A564-1EC7-4657-AECC-CDE009384C7E"><gtr:id>C984A564-1EC7-4657-AECC-CDE009384C7E</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Marco</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Tripodi</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_UP_1201%2F2"><gtr:id>C6A95805-16AD-40DC-AB04-ECD277BB5EF1</gtr:id><gtr:title>Core - Neural circuitry of action: function and dysfunction</gtr:title><gtr:status>Active</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_UP_1201/2</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Let?s think of an action that we perform daily and effortlessly such as grasping a cup of tea before going to work. This seemingly simple action highlights one of the major task that the nervous system faces, that of linking perception to action. Upon perceiving the location of any object we are capable of interacting with it and direct our movements towards it. The complexity of this task is multifaceted, first we need to precisely locate the position of the object with respect to our own ever-changing body position, then we need to articulate over 50 individual muscles in order to move our hand towards the exact location of the target. Our goal is to understand how the surrounding space is encoded and embedded in a motor program that allows us to physically interact with it. We study this problem in mice, by trying to dissect the neuronal circuits responsible for transforming spatial perception into an appropriate pattern of movements. With our work we hope to gain new insights into how motor networks are assembled and how perception is integrated into motor action. Understanding the nature of these circuits, the genetics of them, how they are assembled and how they function is fundamental for the understanding of how we produce purposeful movements and why we fail to do so at the onset of motor disorders.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Movement is our only way to interact with the environment, to explore it and modify it. We study the organization and function of neural circuits controlling movement in mice, with particular focus on goal oriented movements. We seek to understand three fundamental aspects of motor control: 1) How animals produce an accurate body-bound map of the surrounding space that can be used to direct targeted movements 2) Which neuronal populations are directly involved in orchestrating goal-oriented movements towards salient positions of this map 3) How, during development, these neuronal populations are assembled into functional networks with the degree of specificity needed to coordinate movements.
In order to answer these questions we focus on the motor network controlling head movements. The head movement system has the advantage of being relatively simple, if compared to the limb system, with only one individual joint and a limited set of muscles. Moreover, in rodents, target directed head movements are possibly the most commonly used strategy to interact with the world. The reduced dimensionality of these systems offers an unprecedented opportunity to reconstruct the complete connectome of a motor network. This will facilitate our understanding of the genetics of its assembly and logic of its function.
In line with our focus on neural circuits, we also work on the development of novel methods to trace and manipulate neural circuits in vivo in ways that are not currently possible. The main aim of this part of the work is the development of non-cytotoxic trans-synaptic tracers that would allow long-term circuit manipulation, recording and visualization. Using these methods, we aim at understanding the contribution of network dynamics to motor function as well as understanding the molecular underpinning of neural-networks communication in health and disease.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2013-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>2349120</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>1495731</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>European Union (EU)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>EUR</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>Austria</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>de_AT</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>ERC Starting Grant</gtr:description><gtr:end>2020-12-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>European Research Council (ERC)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>677029 - Space and Motion</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>F790A24A-DC15-4BA1-83CC-5E0A6DCF7E4C</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56cb105ac045f0.79251660</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>65766</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Studentship